explanation: The loop used for s in S: iterated over every character of the raw input string, so any spaces (or other separators) became characters passed to int(), causing a ValueError on ' ' or other non-digit characters. I fixed it by iterating over the whitespace-separated tokens using S.split(), so each token is a valid numeric string to convert with int().
fixed_code:
S = input()
num = set([i for i in range(1, 10)])

for s in S.split():
    num.discard(int(s))

print(*num)
